@mivanac That isn't exactly what I am asking but it would work too. In that way you would always return a new `InetSocketAddress` via `InetSocketAddress.createUnresolved()`.

My suggestion was to not even use an `InetSocketAddress` in the `LocatorAddress`, but I think your approach works too.

I think we should make sure that the `InetSocketAddress` inside the `LocatorAddress` is unresolved as well. Its not the end of the world if it is but there isn't much point to it ever resolving.

Hey @nabarunnag ,

Thanks for reviewing!.
I don't know the answer to your question, though, apparently the flag was not always set on the `QueryExecutionContext` for CQs, that's why I had to add the constructor parameter. On the other hand, the `reset()` method was added for CQs only a long time ago, so we apparently want to reset the context before the actual execution... we can create another ticket and investigate this further, I'm hesitant to change this behaviour right now without knowing all the implications.

```
  /**
   * Added to reset the state from the last execution. This is added for CQs only.
   */
  @Override
  public void reset() {
    super.reset();
    this.execCacheStack.clear();
  }
```
